structured content, and

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:38.722
completely lose it
on the way out.

00:23:38.722 --> 00:23:44.420
Schema.org allows you to put
those semantics back in.

00:23:44.420 --> 00:23:45.110
So how do you do this?

00:23:45.110 --> 00:23:48.720
The first thing you do is by
circumscribing the universe of

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:51.080
discourse that you're talking
about, simply just by adding

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:54.840
the itemscope property to
the top-level div that

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:57.200
encapsulates all the information
about this song.

00:23:57.200 --> 00:24:00.540
Itemscope basically just
says, this is a thing.

00:24:00.540 --> 00:24:02.510
The next attribute you add
is itemtype, which says

00:24:02.510 --> 00:24:04.180
what type it is.

00:24:04.180 --> 00:24:09.150
The types are all enumerated at
schema.org/docs/full.html.

00:24:09.150 --> 00:24:10.450
In this particular case,
we're talking

00:24:10.450 --> 00:24:11.710
about a music recording.

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:14.410
Now within the type of music
recording, a lot of additional

00:24:14.410 --> 00:24:17.630
attributes can apply, that
map very directly to this

00:24:17.630 --> 00:24:18.850
particular DOM.

00:24:18.850 --> 00:24:21.970
All of these are marked via
itemprop attributes.

00:24:21.970 --> 00:24:26.490
So you just add itemprop
to the DOM accordingly.

00:24:26.490 --> 00:24:28.520
